Introduction

Many statistical methods require complete datasets.Often, this is not the case and observations with missing values are simply removed leading to potential bias. This report will summarise the main findings of a missing data analysis and discuss the results of several imputation techniques followed by regressions.

Question 1

Implementation of the multiple imputation and nonparametric bootstrap. The code can be found in the accompanied uploaded files on Blackboard.

Question 2

Next we perform a simulation study to investigate the behavior of OLS and MM-regression after (1) single kNN imputation and (2) multiple iterative model based imputation. The following combinations of situations are investigated:

  • Missing data mechanism
    • Missing at Random (MAR) and Missing Not at Random (MNAR)
  • Amount of missingness
    • 10%, 25% and 50% missing values
  • Outlier types
    • Vertical, good leverage and bad leverage outliers
  • Outlier contamination levels
    • 10%, 25% and 50% outliers

In all cases a total of 100 observations are used. To simulate a MNAR mechanism we calculate a probability vector which is consequently used as probability that this observation will be removed from the data. A situation where lower values of \(x\) are more likely to be missing than higher values, is achieved by calculating the probabilities as \(1/x\). The true data generating process before contamination with outliers and removing observations is described by equation:

\(y\) ~ \(\alpha\) \(+\) \(\beta\) \(*\) \(x\)

where \(\alpha\) \(=\) \(100\), \(\beta\) \(=\) \(2\) and \(\sigma\) \(=\) \(40\)

Only a selection of interesting results will be discussed, as these elements lead to 54 combinations of $and \(\beta\) for OLS and MM. All combinations of the simulation scenarios are found in the accompanied Excell file upload on Blackboard. Three examples of scenarios are shown in Figure 1 below. The title indicates the outlier type, the amount of missingness and the missing data mechanism.

Figure 1: Examples of scenarios

1: Results after single kNN imputation

The most accurate estimates are unsurprisingly obtained in case of good leverage outliers for all contamination levels and missingness combinations, even for 50% outliers and 50% missingness. In general we find that OLS and MM yield comparable accuracy in all MNAR situations. In case of MCAR the best accuracy is often achieved by MM.

The worst estimates are given by the combination of bad leverage outliers with 50% MNAR values for both OLS and MM. These results are shown in Table 1. The regressions are clearly influenced by the bad outliers. Both the intercept and the slope are underestimated in case of 25% of outliers and 50% of outliers.

Table 2 displays the results of bad leverage outliers with 10% MCAR values, both OLS and MM are now already influenced by the outliers, even in case of only 10% outliers. We find that the resulting estimates are not accurate compared to vertical outliers or good leverage outliers with equal amounts of missingness.

Bonus

In case of multiple datasets we have the luxury to to compare results instead of deciding on a single set. Taking all imputed datasets as reference instead of looking at values within a single imputated dataset leads to less uncertainty. If the same outlying points appears in a large portion of the imputed datasets it is more likely this point is actually an outlier.

Question 3

To conclude we will analyse the biopics dataset by [FiveThirtyEight, 2015]. The data contains information regarding biographical movies scraped from the website IMDb.com. Table 3 displays overview of the variables included and an example observation. The included variables are self-explanatory based on their names. For the factor variables the first level is defined as base-level. A quick analysis reveals that in general most biographical movies feature a white male subject. The reponse variable box office is a monetary variable with high values and variation. Thus, we log transform box office, this also increases interpretability of the regression estimations.

Missing Data Analysis

As can be seen in the example in Table 3 not all observations are included and we have to deal with missing data. We start by looking at the missing data and the pattern. Table 4 shows a summary of the missingness. Approximately 40% of the movies have no missing information and there are no cases where there are more than 2 variables missing. 60% of the movies have at least one missing value.

Table 4: Summary of missing data
# of Missing by Case # of Cases Percentage
0 270 40.4
1 328 49.1
2 70 10.5

Figure 2: Missing data and pattern in Biopics

Figure 2 reveals that only box office is missing in roughly 33% and only subject race is missing in 16% of the observations. These variables are missing together in the same observation for 10% of the movies. This amounts to a total of 60% as stated.

There are three distinct cases of missing data: MCAR, MAR, MNAR [Little & Rubin, 2002]. MNAR is most problematic for further analysis but in all cases information is lost by omitting incomplete observations. Estimating the missing values, imputation, will likely yield more reliable results.

In assumption of random missingness the boxplots in Figure 3 should be similar, we see that this is not the case. In these examples the marginplot reveals that subject race is missing more often in newer movies. It also shows that there are many biographical movies with a white subject race (corresponding to the value 0.2 on the x-axis). On contrary, box office is missing more often in older movies. Furthermore, we see that higher box office amounts occur more frequently in newer released movies. In short; the missing data mechanism does not appear to be random in the biopocics data.

Figure 3: Margin plot of Biopics data

Figure 3 displays some outlying observations with a very high box office compared to the general expected pattern; two in the top right around 2010 and one around 1965. The movies belonging to these observations are shown in Table 5, they are all produced in the same country, US, but cover a different subject.

Imputation

Next, we investigate regressions using box office as response variable in three cases: (1) after simply excluding incomplete cases, (2) after kNN imputation with bootstrapped standard errors and (3) after multiple iterative model-based imputation. Since a large portion of our observations contain missing values we expect approach (1) to give biased results and approach (2) and (3) to be more reliable and yield more comparable results.

We found title is not missing in any of the cases and is unique for every movie. However, this variable may provide information and disregarding this in the regression does not seem smart. Therefore, an extra numeric variable is added to the analysis that represents the length of the title. It is a possibility there exists a relation between box office and the length of the title of the movie.

1: Ignoring incomplete cases

First, an easy solution and common approach is taken by simply removing observations containing missing values. This leads to ignoring information regarding 60% of the movies in our data. The result are likely biased since we have found our missing values are MNAR.

Interpretation of Results

Figure 4 below displays the fit after OLS and MM regression. We find that OLS yields higher box office values than MM. Again we find the outlier belonging to the movie American Sniper in the top right of both plots.

Figure 4: OLS and MM fit after omitting NA’s

Including the full variable selection in the regression yields differing results for OLS and MM. In the OLS regression the following variables are significant:

  • Country (Canada): Negative effect on box office
  • Country (UK): Negative effect on box office
  • Subject Type (Actor/Actress): Negative effect on box office
  • Subject Gender (Female): Positive effect on box office

In the MM regression the following variables are significant:

  • Country (Canada): Negative effect on box office
  • Country (UK): Negative effect on box office
  • Subject Type (Actor/Actress): Negative effect on box office
  • Subject Type (Author): Negative effect on box office

In order to compare goodness of fit we calculate accuracy metrics for the two regressions. Since we have presence of outliers the MSPE is not the best choice, as this metric is highly influenced by outliers. The MAPE is also not optimal due to giving equal weights to all observations. A better option is the MAD, as the median is a robust measure of univariate location which is the case for residuals. MM provides a better fit than OLS based on the MAD.

MAD of OLS regression MAD of MM regression
1.381085 1.337685

3: Multiple iterative model-based imputation

The main advantage of this method is that valid inference can be performed in case of missing values. In theory multiple imputation can work for all three types of missing data but MNAR is more complicated. The uncertainty induced between the multiple imputed datasets reflect the uncertainty caused by the missing values [van Buuren, 1999]. The amount of imputations \(m\) is set approximately equal to the percentage of incomplete observations as suggested by [Bodner, 2008] and [White et al. 2011]. For the biopics data we use \(m=60\) imputations. To impute the numerical values for box office predictive mean matching (pmm) is used. For subject race Bayesian polytomous regression (polyreg) is used, which is the default for unordered factors with more than two levels.

Before we interpret the results it is interesting to inspect the imputations we have done. It is of importance that the imputation yields reliable values compared to the values that are observed.

Figure 5: Density Comparison

Figure 5 compares the densities of box office in the imputed dataset with the density of box office in the originally observed data. Some deviation is to be expected from imputing the data 60 times and may actually be of use. This will incorporate uncertainty from the missing values into our analysis. The imputed values seem to be a bit higher on average than the observed values for lower box office values. However, the central tendency and overall shape of the densities appear to be comparable.

Predictive performance

To test predictive performance of our regression models we split the data set into a training and testing set. For training we use 70% and for testing 30%. Since we have some outlying observations it is of importance to obtain samples that are comparable in terms of amount of outliers. Fitting the model on a training sample where all outliers are included or testing the model on a sample where all outliers are included is not the most reliable approach.

Conclusion

After analysing the biopics dataset by means of kNN imputations on bootstrapped samples and multiple model based imputations followed by OLS and MM regressions we conclude that the following relations hold;

  • Country 2 (Canada): Negative effect on box office
  • Country 4 (UK): Negative effect on box office
  • Subject Type (Actor/Actress): Negative effect on box office
  • Subject Type (Author): Negative effect on box office

The following relation is found in case of OLS regression * Subject Gender (Female): Positive effect on box office

On this dataset comparable relations are found by simply removing observations with missing values

Regarding Robust Methods

I do not think that robust methods are neccesary in this application of multiple imputation. We find that the OLS and MM regression give comparable results. Furthermore, the goal of imputation is to introduce uncertainty to account for the uncertainty due to missingness. If small amounts of outlying observations occur due to imputation in some of the \(m\) datasets their influence is likely small due to pooling all imputed sets in the end. Furthermore, if outlying observations occur more frequently through the imputation procedure, this could be an indication that these “outliers” are actually a plausible observation in the true distribution based on the rest of the data which is used for imputing the data. Ofcourse, this can not be said with absolute certainty since the true distribution is unknown. In general, I would think that taking a sufficient amount of multiple imputed datasets will minimize the potential harmfull effects of outliers on the results.
